Question 1

## Given: IRS and CRA wants to determine the easy filling tax form between the current and three newly developed taxforms
## To do: Conduct ANOVA test to determine if the time taken to fill out the different form is significantly different
## Completely Randomized Design has been followed for this experimentation
irs_1 <- read.csv("IRS 1.csv") ##Load the dataset
irs_st_1 <- stack(irs_1) ## stack the dataset
colnames(irs_st_1) <- c("fill_time","form_type")
head(irs_st_1,1)
##   fill_time form_type
## 1        23    Form.1
summary(irs_1)

1.a

## Checking the normality by plotting the histograms for each form type
ggplot(irs_1, aes(x=Form.1)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 40) + ggtitle("Form 1 Sample Distribution") + xlab("Form 1") + ylab("Frequency")

ggplot(irs_1, aes(x=Form.2)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 40) + ggtitle("Form 1 Sample Distribution") + xlab("Form 2") + ylab("Frequency")

ggplot(irs_1, aes(x=Form.3)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 40) + ggtitle("Form 1 Sample Distribution") + xlab("Form 3") + ylab("Frequency")

ggplot(irs_1, aes(x=Form.4)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 40) + ggtitle("Form 1 Sample Distribution") + xlab("Form 4") + ylab("Frequency")

## As the sample size is low and since no clear pattern from histogram, we can test our normality and constant variances conditions on the residuals and statistical tests
lm_irs_1 <- lm(irs_st_1$fill_time ~ irs_st_1$form_type)

irs_1_resids <- residuals(lm_irs_1) ## Reisduals
irs_1_preds <- predict(lm_irs_1) ## Predictions

irs_and_dr <- nortest::ad.test(irs_1_resids) ## Anderson Darling Test
## As the p-value (0.225) from Anderson Darling Test to check normality is greater than our significance value, we failed to reject the null hypothesis i.e. data is sampled from the normally distributed population.
## Moreover the Q-Q plots and histogram plots of the residuals suggest the same

1.b

## To check variances among the different form types filling times

irs_1_levens <- car::leveneTest(irs_st_1$fill_time ~ irs_st_1$form_type)
irs_1_levens$`Pr(>F)`[1]
## [1] 0.969029
## As the p-value (0.969) from Levenes Test to check variance constant condition is greater than our significance value, we failed to reject the null hypothesis i.e. there is constant variance among the groups
## Moreover the boxplots suggest not a big difference in variances among the different form type fill times

1.c

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(\mu_{1}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{2}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{3}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{4}\)

\(H_{1}\) : Atleast one mean is different

## Null Hypothesis: Form fill times across the 4 different form types is same
## Alternate Hypothesis: Atleas 1 form fill time is different from the others
anova_irs_1 <- aov(irs_st_1$fill_time ~ irs_st_1$form_type)
summary(anova_irs_1)
##                     Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## irs_st_1$form_type   3   8464    2821   2.936 0.0363 *
## Residuals          116 111480     961                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## Since the p-value (0.036) is less than our significance value (0.05), we can reject our null hypothesis and conclude that the mean fill times of atleast 1 form type is different from one of the other form types

1.d

tukey_irs_ques_1 <- TukeyHSD(anova_irs_1)
tukey_irs_ques_1
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level

ggplot(irs_2, aes(x=Form.1)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 40) + ggtitle("Form 1 Sample Distribution") + xlab("Form 1") + ylab("Frequency")

## As the sample size is low and since no clear pattern from histogram, we can test our normality and constant variances conditions on the residuals and statistical tests

irs_and_dr_2

##  Anderson-Darling normality test
##

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(\mu_{1}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{2}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{3}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{4}\)

\(H_{1}\) : Atleast one mean is different

## Null Hypothesis: Form fill times across the 4 different forms is same
## Alternate Hypothesis: Atleast 1 form fill time is different from the others
anova_irs_2 <- aov(irs_st_2$fill_time ~ irs_st_2$form_type + irs_st_2$tax_payer)

## Since the p-value (2.2e-10) is less than our significance value (0.05), we can reject our null hypothesis and conclude that the mean fill time of atleast 1 form type is different from one of others

2.d

## Since different persons have different understanding capabilities as well as writing capabilities, experimenting the forms with different people isn't a great solution. So, experimenting same set of people with all the different forms would remove those dependencies theoretically while statstically we are reducing the SSE by introducing with the SSB (blocking error).
## ***We can also see that the taxpayer p value  (2e-16) that its significantly having the different means suggesting the blocking is effective***
TukeyHSD(anova_irs_2, which = 'irs_st_2$form_type', ordered=TRUE)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
##     factor levels have been ordered

2.f

## Since the introduction of the block design we reduced the residual error (SSE). Essentially the (MSE) decreasing while increasing the F-value so we are able to capture the difference in means more effectively and that's the reason we have more number of differences compared to the question 1. 
## ***Simply, the efficiency of the capturing the differences between the means of fill times between the form types increased by using Randomized Block Design compared to the Completely Randomzied Design***

2.g

## While using the RBD design the SSE value is 5764, but with the CRD design we have SSE as 111480, the fall in the SSE value is due to introducing the block design which is capturing the majority of the residual variation (SSB).
## ***So the within variation (SSE) in question 2 has been reduced by the block design i.e. SSB***

Question 3

## Given: Experimentation was done based on people filling IRS tax returns forms by grouping at 3 income levels
## To do: ANOVA hyothesis testing on the experimentation to determine if there any interactions
## Complete Factorial Design (Two Factor ANOVA) has been followed for this experimentation design
irs_3 <- read.csv("IRS 3.csv") ##Load the dataset
irs_3$Group <- factor(irs_3$Group)
irs_st_3 <- cbind(irs_3[1], stack(irs_3[2:5]))


colnames(irs_st_3) <- c("Group","fill_times","form_type")
head(irs_st_3,1)
##   Group fill_times form_type
## 1     1         43    Form.1
summary(irs_3)
##  Group      Form.1           Form.2           Form.3          Form.4     
##  1:10   Min.   : 43.00   Min.   : 37.00   Min.   : 57.0   Min.   : 38.0  
##  2:10   1st Qu.: 67.50   1st Qu.: 70.00   1st Qu.: 86.5   1st Qu.: 88.0  
##  3:10   Median : 89.50   Median : 94.50   Median :105.5   Median :105.0  
##         Mean   : 92.97   Mean   : 93.37   Mean   :103.9   Mean   :110.0  
##         3rd Qu.:121.50   3rd Qu.:109.50   3rd Qu.:118.8   3rd Qu.:137.5  
##         Max.   :150.00   Max.   :186.00   Max.   :148.0   Max.   :166.0

3.a

## There are two factors in the experimental design.
##  1. Income Level Groups
##  2. Form Types

3.b

## Under the income level groups factor, there are 3 levels:
##  1. Low Income
##  2. Next Income Bracker
##  3. Highest Bracket
## Under the Form types factor there are 4 levels:
##  1. Form Type 1
##  2. Form Type 2
##  3. Form Type 3
##  4. Form Type 4

3.c

## There are total 12 treatments (4*3) in this Two Factor ANOVA Experimental Design

3.d

## Checking the normality condition
lm_model_3 <- lm(irs_st_3$fill_times ~ irs_st_3$Group + irs_st_3$form_type + irs_st_3$Group*irs_st_3$form_type)
resid_irs_3 <- residuals(lm_model_3)
pred_irs_3 <- predict(lm_model_3)

irs_and_dr_3 <- nortest::ad.test(resid_irs_3) ## Anderson Darling Test
irs_and_dr_3
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  resid_irs_3
## A = 0.29614, p-value = 0.5882
## [1] "As the p-value (0.588) from Anderson Darling Test to check normality is greater than our significance value, we failed to reject the null hypothesis i.e. data is sampled from the normally distributed population\n Moreover the Q-Q plots and histogram plots of the residuals suggest the same"
## Checking the variances among the form type filling times and Income Levels

irs_3_levens <- car::leveneTest(irs_st_3$fill_time ~ irs_st_3$form_type*irs_st_3$Group)
irs_3_levens
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value Pr(>F)
## group  11  0.6365 0.7941
##       108
## As the p-value (0.794) from Levenes Test to check variance constant condition is greater than our significance value, we failed to reject the null hypothesis i.e. there is constant variance among the groups
## Moreover the boxplots suggest not a big difference in variances among the different form type fill times
## Hypothesis to test the interaction

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : Form Type and Income Group do not interact to affect the filling times of the tax forms
\(H_{1}\) : Form Type and Income Group interact to affect the filling times of the tax forms

##                                    Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## irs_st_3$form_type                  3   6280    2093   2.563 0.0586 .
## irs_st_3$Group                      2   6719    3359   4.113 0.0190 *
## irs_st_3$form_type:irs_st_3$Group   6   5102     850   1.041 0.4030  
## Residuals                         108  88217     817                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## Th p-value for the Group and Form Type level is 0.403 greater than the significance value (0.05). So, we fail to reject null hypothesis and conclude that the Form Type and Income Group do not interact to affect the filling times of the tax forms
interaction.plot(irs_st_3$form_type,irs_st_3$Group,irs_st_3$fill_times)

## Although we could some minor overlap/interaction between the form type and income group, it's not a significant and moreover the interaction p-value is significantly high to say that the there is no interaction between the two factors

3.e

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(\mu_{1}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{2}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{3}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{4}\)

\(H_{1}\) : Atleast one mean is different

## The p-value for Gender is 0.059 is greater than the significance level (0.05). So, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that form type has no effect on the form filling times

3.f

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(\mu_{1}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{2}\) \(=\) \(\mu_{3}\)

\(H_{1}\) : Atleast one mean is different

## The p-value for Gender is 0.020 is less than the significance level (0.05). So, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that income bracket has effect on the form filling times
